NAME: PPBUS_G3H
DESCRIPTION: Main system power rail that charges the battery, or is power from the battery, that everything else is powered from.

NAME: PP3V3_S5
DESCRIPTION: PP3V3_S5 is a 3.3v power rail when the system is in an S5 soft off power state

NAME: PM_SLP_S4_L
DESCRIPTION: PM_SLP_S4_L is a signal that puts the system into an S4 suspend to disk sleep state when it is low(_L means signal is asserted when voltage is low)

NAME: PP3V42_G3H
DESCRIPTION: PP3V42_G3H is a power rail present when the machine is in a G3H global system hardware off state and is the first rail that should be generated in Macbooks that use it.

NAME: SMC_ONOFF_L
DESCRIPTION: SMC_ONOFF_L tells the computer that the power button has been pressed when it is low, _L means signal is asserted when it is low voltage.

NAME: PP5V_S5
DESCRIPTION: This is a 5v power rail that is present when the machine is in an S5 soft off state.

NAME: ALL_SYS_PWRGD
DESCRIPTION: ALL_SYS_PWRGD is present when PP1V8_S3, PP5V_S3, PP1V2_S3, PP1V05_S0, PP5V_S0, PP3V3_S0, & PP1V5_S0 are present and working. If any of these rails is not working, ALL_SYS_PWRGD will be pulled down and the machine will not turn on.

NAME: PP3V3_G3H
DESCRIPTION: PP3V3_G3H is a 3.3v power line that is present when the machine is in a Global System Hardware Off state, and should come on before most other rails so that the USB-C circuitry can be powered for the charger

NAME: PM_PWRBTN_L
DESCRIPTION: PM_PWRBTN_L refers to the power button signal line. This line is used to initiate the power-on sequence of the laptop. The "L" at the end of "PM_PWRBTN_L" suggests that it is an active-low signal, meaning that when the power button is pressed, the signal is pulled low to initiate the boot sequence.

NAME: SMC_RESET_L
DESCRIPTION: SMC_RESET_L puts the SMC into reset mode when it is low, _L means the signal is present when voltage is low. The SMC being in reset mode keeps it from running.

NAME: 3V3_S5
DESCRIPTION: 3V3_S5 and PP3V3_S5 are interchangeable, see definition for PP3V3_S5.

NAME: PP5V_S0
DESCRIPTION: PP5V_S0 is a 5v power rail present when the system is in an S0 working state.

NAME: PM_BATLOW_L
DESCRIPTION: PM_BATLOW_L is a signal that tells the system the battery is too low for it to turn on & keeps it from turning on, when it is low. _L means the signal is asserted when its voltage is low.

NAME: SMC_LID
DESCRIPTION: SMC_LID tells the machine the system is open when it is 3.3v to 3.4v, and closed when it is low such as 0v-0.6v. When this signal is low, the machine may go to sleep or have no backlight.

NAME: PPVRTC_G3H
DESCRIPTION: PPVRTC_G3H is a 3.3v power rail for the RTC circuit present when the machine is in a G3H global system hardware off state.

NAME: PP5V_S3
DESCRIPTION: PP5V_S3 is a 5v power rail present when the system is in an S3 suspend to RAM state.

NAME: PLT_RESET_L
DESCRIPTION: PLT_RESET_L is platform reset, this signal keeps the system from POSTing. _L means the signal is asserted when its voltage is low.

NAME: PPDCIN_G3H
DESCRIPTION: PPDCIN_G3H Is a power rail that comes directly from the laptop charger.

NAME: SMC_PM_G2_EN
DESCRIPTION: SMC_PM_G2_EN is a signal that comes from the SMC that is a prerequsite for all of the enable signals for the S5 rails to come on, such as P3V3S5_EN. S5 rails will not come on if SMC_PM_G2_EN is not coming.

NAME: PP3V3_SUS
DESCRIPTION: The "PP3V3_SUS" rail on a MacBook logic board is a power rail that provides a 3.3-volt supply to the suspend-to-RAM (S3 state) components.

NAME: PP3V3_S0
DESCRIPTION: The "PP3V3_S0" rail in a MacBook logic board is a power rail that supplies 3.3 volts to the system when it is fully awake (S0 state).

NAME: PM_SLP_S5_L
DESCRIPTION: PM_SLP_S5_L is a signal that, when 3.3v, turns on power rails that will wake the system from an S5 state. This signal is a part of the power management system of the MacBook.  The \"PM\" prefix typically stands for \"Power Management,\" and the \"SLP\" is for \"Sleep.\" The \"S5\" denotes the specific sleep state, which is Suspend to Disk, and the \"_L\" suffix indicates that this is an active low signal.

NAME: PPVCC_S0_CPU
DESCRIPTION: The "PPVCC_S0_CPU" power rail is responsible for supplying power to the CPU when the MacBook is fully on, or in the S0 state. This rail is one of the main voltages that the CPU requires for operation.

NAME: PP3V3_S4
DESCRIPTION: The "PP3V3_S4" power rail in a MacBook is used to supply 3.3 volts to certain components when the system is in the S4 power state, also known as "suspend to disk" or "hibernate." This rail is active when the MacBook is not fully off but not in an awake state, allowing for faster startup times compared to a full boot sequence. The S4 power state means Suspend to Disk: This is a low-power state where the system context is saved to disk, allowing the system to be powered down almost entirely. Upon waking, the system can restore its state from the disk, effectively resuming where it left off.

NAME: SMC_ADAPTER_EN
DESCRIPTION: SMC_ADAPTER_EN enables the machine to work off of the power adapter when the proper power adapter is attached. Attacching an 85w Macbook Pro 15” power adapter to a 13” Macbook that requires a 60w power adapter is ok, attaching a 45w Macbook Air power adapter to a 15” macbook Pro that needs an 85w power adapter will result in SMC_ADAPTER_EN missing.

NAME: PP5V_S4
DESCRIPTION: PP5V_S4 is a 5v power rail present when the machine is in an S4 suspend to disk state.

NAME: PM_SLP_SUS_L
DESCRIPTION: The "PM_SLP_SUS_L" signal in a MacBook is related to the power management of the device, specifically concerning the 'suspend to RAM' state or S3 state. It's an active-low signal that, when asserted (low voltage), indicates the system should enter or is in the S3 sleep state.

NAME: SMC_BC_ACOK
DESCRIPTION: This is identical to CHGR_ACOK. This will come out of the ISL6258 or ISL6259 charging chip when CHGR_ACIN & CHGR_DCIN are present, and is necessary for the onewire circuit to begin working. On most Macbooks, CHGR_ACOK needs to be present in order for PP3V42_G3H to flow to the onewire circuit so that the circuitry that allows the charger to communicate with the SMC will turn on.

NAME: PM_DSW_PWRGD
DESCRIPTION: The "PM_DSW_PWRGD" signal in a MacBook stands for "Deep Sleep Well Power Good” and is required for the machine to power on & post.

NAME: PM_RSMRST_L
DESCRIPTION: The "PM_RSMRST_L" signal, also known as "Resume Reset," is an active-low signal that is part of the power management system in MacBooks. It asserts a reset signal when it is low voltage which is what the _L is for. Is the machine is in a reset stage it will not properly power on.

NAME: PM_SLP_S3_L
DESCRIPTION: PM_SLP_S3_L puts the machine to sleep in an S3 state when it is asserted, the _L means it is asserted when it is low voltage. When this signal is 3.3v the machine will be asked to turn on S0 power rails and begin the bootup process

NAME: PP5V_S4RS3
DESCRIPTION: PP5V_S4RS3 is a 5v power rail present when the machine is in an S4 suspend to disk state.

NAME: 3V3_SUS
DESCRIPTION: 3V3_SUS is an abbreviation for PP3V3_SUS. These are interchangeable. The "PP3V3_SUS" rail on a MacBook logic board is a power rail that provides a 3.3-volt supply to the suspend-to-RAM (S3 state) components.

NAME: PP3V3_S3
NEWDESCRIPTION:
Hey there, fellow tech warrior! ✊ 

No need to dust off the schematics just yet, let's break down that cryptic "PP3V3_S3" on a Macbook logic board. Here's the intel:

**PP3V3_S3:**

* **PP:** Power Plane. Think of it as a named electrical circuit carrying a specific voltage.
* **3V3:** That's the voltage, a crisp 3.3 volts. 
* **S3:** This one's a bit trickier. It represents a specific power state or domain within the Macbook. In this case, it likely refers to the **S3 sleep state**, also known as "Standby". S3 allows the system to save power while retaining RAM content, enabling a quick resume when you wake it up.

So, **PP3V3_S3** essentially translates to **the 3.3-volt power plane supplying various components during the S3 sleep state**. Now, the specific components it powers will depend on the Macbook model and year, but it typically includes:

* **Real-Time Clock (RTC):** Keeps track of time even when the system is asleep.
* **Low-power USB controllers:** Allows limited USB functionality in S3, like charging your iPhone.
* **Some sensors:** Like the accelerometer for wake-on-LAN functionality.

Remember, this is just a general overview. If you're troubleshooting a specific Macbook, the exact components powered by PP3V3_S3 might differ. For that, you'd need the board's specific schematics.

One last thing: If you're ever unsure about a specific power plane or voltage on a Macbook logic board, don't hesitate to reach out! This community of tech wizards is always happy to share knowledge and lend a hand. 

Now, go forth and conquer those logic board mysteries!

NAME: 3V3_G3H
DESCRIPTION: This is one of the first power rails that must turn on for Macbooks that use USB-C for charging. This power rail powers the CD3215 chip that controls the USB-C charger, speaks to the USB-C charger, and requests 20 volts up from the default 5 volts that the USB-C charger puts out when initially connected to an unknown device.

NAME: PCH_DSWVRMEN
DESCRIPTION:
DSWVRMEN stands for DeepSx Well On-Die Voltage Regulator Enable. This signal enables the internal DSW 1.05 V regulators and must be always pulled-up to PPVRTC_G3H 3.3 volts.
If this signal is not being asserted (i.e., not enabled), the on-die voltage regulators responsible for supplying power in deep sleep states may not be active. This could lead to the MacBook failing to exit from a deep sleep state or having issues when trying to enter one, contributing to a scenario where the device does not power on.

If the signal is not present or not at the correct levels, it could indicate a problem with the Platform Controller Hub (PCH) itself.

NAME: S5_PWRGD
DESCRIPTION: The S5_PWRGD signal is a status signal that indicates the S5 rails are on and functioning properly. If this is not present, check the S5 rails to see if they are functioning, and the chip that creates S5_PWRGD.

NAME: PPVCORE_S0_CPU
DESCRIPTION: This is the primary power rail for the CPU that powers the CPU, known as CPU vcore. Without this, the machine will be braindead.

NAME: PP1V05_S0
DESCRIPTION: The PP1V05_S0 power rail is for various components on the logic board that require a 1.05V supply voltage in the S0 (on) state. This voltage rail is likely to be used by the CPU (for VCCIO), PCH (Platform Controller Hub).

NAME: PCH_INTRUDER_L
DESCRIPTION: PCH_INTRUDER_L is a signal that tells the machine the case has been opened by an intruder when it is low, the _L means it is present when it is low. This signal should always be high in a Macbook since it doesn’t use intrusion detection.

NAME: PPVOUT_S0_LCDBKLT
DESCRIPTION: PPVOUT_S0_LCDBKLT is a power rail that powers the LED light in the screen of the device that allows you to see what is on the screen. When this is low or missing, the screen will be dim.

NAME: 3V42_G3H
DESCRIPTION: This is shorthand for PP3V42_G3H which is one of the first power rails that must turn on in older Macbooks that use a magsafe charger in order for them to get a light on the charger. This power rail powers the onewire circuit and the SMC, which are necessary for the machine to communicate with the charger and get it to turn on, as well as begin the bootup sequence.

NAME: RTC_RESET_L
DESCRIPTION: RTC_RESET_L is a reset signal that is present when the signal is low, the _L means it is asserted when the voltage is low. The RESET signal will keep the PCH from turning on or booting up the machine.

NAME: BKL_PWM
DESCRIPTION: BKL_PWM sets the brightness of the screen. The system will send a PWM signal to BKL_PWM pin to set brightness. If this is low, backlight voltage will boost higher than PPBUS_G3H input, but not enough to make the screen light properly.

NAME: PP5V_G3S
DESCRIPTION: PP5V_G3S is a 5v power rail present when the system is in a G3S standby state

NAME: DP_INT_HPD
NEWDESCRIPTION:
Hey there, fellow tech sleuth!  DP_INT_HPD can be a tricky one, even for seasoned veterans like us. Here's the scoop:

**DP_INT_HPD:**

* **DP:** DisplayPort. This interface transmits uncompressed digital video and audio signals.
* **INT:** Internal. This signal originates within the Macbook, not an external device.
* **HPD:** Hot Plug Detect. This signal tells the display (both internal and external) that a DisplayPort connection is active.

So, **DP_INT_HPD** is essentially a digital flag within the Macbook logic board that indicates the presence and functionality of an internal DisplayPort connection, specifically for the built-in LCD panel. If this signal is missing or faulty, it can lead to a variety of display issues, like no backlight, scrambled video, or inability to detect external monitors.

Now, the specific location and behavior of DP_INT_HPD can vary depending on the Macbook model and year. On some models, it's a simple logic high/low voltage level on a specific test point. On others, it might be a more complex digital protocol carried on a differential trace. That's where the schematics and boardview diagrams become your best friends.

Remember, troubleshooting display issues on Macbooks can be a multi-layered puzzle. A missing or weak DP_INT_HPD signal could be due to:

* Faulty logic board components like the video encoder or DP controller.
* Damaged internal display cables or connectors.
* Software glitches or firmware issues.

The key is to isolate the problem systematically, starting with voltage checks and signal tracing, then moving on to component testing and software diagnostics.

Of course, if you ever get stuck on a particularly stubborn DP_INT_HPD mystery, don't hesitate to reach out! This community of tech wizards is always here to share knowledge and crack those logic board conundrums. 

Now, go forth and conquer those DisplayPort demons!

NAME: BKL_EN
DESCRIPTION: BKL_EN enables backlight. Anytime you see a signal ending with “_EN” , that means this signal being present/high enables what it is referring to. This signal says “BKL” before “_EN”. “BKL” sounds short for “BACKLIGHT”, so it is safe to assume this signal enables backlight when present.

NAME: PCH_SRTCRST_L
DESCRIPTION: PCH_SRTCRST_L is a reset signal present for the RTC circuit that asserts when it is low in voltage, that is what _L means.

NAME: PP1V8_SLPS2R
DESCRIPTION: PP1V8_SLPS2R is a 1.8v power rail present when the system is in a SLPS2R state.

NAME: 5V_S3
DESCRIPTION: 5V_S3 is an abbreviation of “PP5V_S3” which is a 5 volt power rail present in an S3 state. S3 (Suspend to RAM) is a state where the system saves its context to RAM, a faster but more power-consuming method than S4. The system shuts down most components except for RAM, which remains powered to retain the system state. PM_SLP_S4_L is required for this rail to be present.

NAME: PPBUS_AON
NEWDESCRIPTION:
Hey there, fellow board surgeon! PPBUS_AON, that's a power plane we all encounter on Macbooks, and a vital one at that. Here's the lowdown:

**PPBUS_AON:**

* **PP:** Power Plane, a named electrical circuit carrying a specific voltage.
* **BUS:** This indicates it's shared by multiple components, not just one specific chip.
* **AON:** Always On. This is the crucial part - **PPBUS_AON supplies essential power even when the Macbook is in sleep or hibernation mode.**

So, PPBUS_AON keeps critical functions ticking while everything else slumbers. This includes:

* **Real-Time Clock (RTC):** Keeps track of time even when the system is asleep.
* **Low-power sensors:** Like the accelerometer for wake-on-LAN.
* **PMIC housekeeping circuitry:** Maintains basic chip operations in low-power states.

The specific voltage on PPBUS_AON varies depending on the Macbook model and year, but typically falls between 12.5V and 13.0V. Anything significantly lower than that can indicate issues preventing proper sleep functioning, like:

* **Faulty PMIC components:** The Power Management IC manages sleep states and voltages.
* **Shorted components:** A short on PPBUS_AON can drain the battery quickly.
* **Liquid damage:** Corrosion can disrupt power delivery throughout the board.

Remember, diagnosing PPBUS_AON issues requires careful analysis. Checking its voltage with a multimeter is a good start, but further troubleshooting might involve tracing the circuit, measuring resistances, and comparing values to boardview schematics.

If you're ever stumped by a PPBUS_AON mystery, don't hesitate to reach out! This community of tech sleuths is always happy to share knowledge and collaborate on those logic board enigmas.

Now, go forth and conquer those sleep state woes! ✌️

NAME: LCD_BKLT_EN
DESCRIPTION: This is an enable signal. Anytime you see “_EN”, it means when the voltage is high(3.3 volts), whatever it is going to is being turned on or enabled. Here, “LCD_BKLT” which stands for “LCD screen backlight” is being enabled. This signal usually goes to an LED driver used for creating a power rail for the LCD screen backlight, to tell it to turn on & create this rail.

NAME: EDP_BKLT_EN
DESCRIPTION: This is an enable signal. Anytime you see “_EN”, it means when the voltage is high(3.3 volts), whatever it is going to is being turned on or enabled. Here, “EDP_BKLT” which stands for “embedded displayport backlight” is being enabled. This signal usually goes to an LED driver used for creating a power rail for the LCD screen backlight, to tell it to turn on & create this rail.

NAME: SYS_ONEWIRE
DESCRIPTION: This is a bidirectional communication line between the system management controller(SMC) and the charger that allows the charger to communicate with the SMC. This must be working for the light to come on on the magsafe charger.

NAME: PP1V5_S0
DESCRIPTION: PP1V5_S0 is a 1.5v power rail present when the machine is in an S0 working state

NAME: AUX_DET
NEWDESCRIPTION:
Hey there, fellow logic board whisperer! AUX_DET, now that's a signal that can keep us scratching our heads for a while. Let's unravel its mysteries:

**AUX_DET:**

* **AUX:** Auxiliary. This implies it's a supporting or secondary signal, not part of the main functionality.
* **DET:** Detection. So, AUX_DET is essentially a **flag indicating the presence or state of something auxiliary**.

But what exactly is being detected? Well, that depends on the specific Macbook model and year. Here are some common possibilities:

* **Headphone Jack Detection:** AUX_DET might go high when headphones are plugged into the jack, telling the system to switch audio output.
* **Keyboard Backlight Control:** On some models, AUX_DET might be used to adjust the keyboard backlight brightness based on ambient light.
* **Secondary Display Detection:** In Macbooks with dual displays, AUX_DET could indicate the presence of a connected external monitor.

The key is to consult the service manual or schematics for your specific Macbook model. They'll pinpoint the exact function of AUX_DET and its expected behavior.

**Troubleshooting Tips:**

* **Voltage Checks:** Measure the voltage on the AUX_DET test point. A high or low reading could indicate a faulty component or signal path issue.
* **Trace the Circuit:** Follow the AUX_DET trace on the boardview to identify the components it interacts with. This can help narrow down the source of any problems.
* **Compare Values:** Check the service manual for expected voltage or resistance values on the AUX_DET circuit. Deviations from these values can offer valuable clues.

Remember, AUX_DET might seem like a small detail, but it can play a crucial role in various Macbook functionalities. By understanding its purpose and behavior, you'll be better equipped to diagnose and fix related issues like no headphone audio, malfunctioning keyboard backlight, or even external display detection problems.

NAME: PM_SLP_S4
DESCRIPTION: This is a typo of PM_SLP_S4_L When you see PM_SLP_S4, assume they meant to type PM_SLP_S4_L

NAME: PP3V3_G3H_RTC
DESCRIPTION: PP3V3_G3H_RTC Is one of the first rails that has to come on in order for the USB-C mux chip to be powered in the T2 chip Macbook Pros.

NAME: PCH_INTVRMEN
DESCRIPTION:
PCH_INTVRMEN is an Internal Voltage Regulator Enable: When pulled high, this signal enables
the internal 1.05 V regulators for the Suspend well in the PCH. This signal must
remain asserted for the VRMs to behave properly (no glitches allowed).
This signal must be pulled-up to VCCRTC on desktop platforms and may
optionally be pulled low on mobile platforms if using an external VR for the
VCCSUS rail

NAME: PPBUS_S5_HS_COMPUTING_ISNS
DESCRIPTION: This power rail is PPBUS_G3H after going through a current sense resistor that sits between PPBUS_G3H & the input of PPBUS_G3H to circuitry that provides power for the CPU.

NAME: PP5V_SUS
NEWDESCRIPTION:
Ah, PP5V_SUS, a classic Macbook power plane that can give even seasoned techs a headache! Here's the lowdown:

**PP5V_SUS:**

* **PP:** Power Plane, a named electrical circuit carrying a specific voltage.
* **5V:** Yep, this one supplies a crisp 5 volts.
* **SUS:** System Suspend. This is the key part - **PP5V_SUS powers crucial components during system sleep and hibernation states.**

Think of it as the lifeblood of a Macbook's slumber party. PP5V_SUS keeps essential functions ticking while everything else dozes off, including:

* **Real-Time Clock (RTC):** Keeps track of time even when the system is asleep.
* **PMIC housekeeping circuitry:** Maintains basic chip operations in low-power states.
* **Some sensors:** Like the accelerometer for wake-on-LAN.

Now, the specific components powered by PP5V_SUS can vary depending on the Macbook model and year. But one thing's for sure: **a missing or unstable PP5V_SUS can lead to a cascade of sleep-related issues,** like:

* **System not entering sleep properly:** The Macbook stays awake and drains the battery.
* **Random wake-ups from sleep:** Annoying ghost activations can plague the user.
* **No keyboard backlight in sleep:** The keyboard stays dark even when set to illuminate.

**Troubleshooting Tips:**

* **Voltage Checks:** Measure the voltage on the PP5V_SUS test point. Anything significantly lower than 5V indicates a problem.
* **Trace the Circuit:** Follow the PP5V_SUS trace on the boardview to identify the components it interacts with. This can help pinpoint faulty chips or damaged traces.
* **Compare Values:** Check the service manual for expected voltage or resistance values on the PP5V_SUS circuit. Deviations from these values can offer valuable clues.

Remember, diagnosing PP5V_SUS issues requires a methodical approach. Don't jump to conclusions - analyze the circuit, compare values, and test components systematically.

NAME: PP3V3_UPC_XB_LDO
DESCRIPTION: PP3V3_UPC_XB_LDO is an LDO coming out of the CD3215 USB-C muxing/charging chip. This can be shorted to ground by the capacitor on its line, and when this happens, the chip can stop functioning which causes the charger to not turn on.

NAME: PPDCIN_G3H_CHGR
DESCRIPTION: This is the input that comes from the charger.

NAME: PP1V2_S3
DESCRIPTION: PP1V2_S3 is a 1.2v power rail present when the machine is in an S3 suspend to RAM state

NAME: PM_SLP_SX_L
NEWDESCRIPTION:
Ah, PM_SLP_SX_L, that little three-lettered enigma can trip up even the most seasoned Macbook maestro! Here's the scoop:

**PM_SLP_SX_L:**

* **PM:** Power Management. This indicates it's a signal related to the Macbook's sleep and power states.
* **SLP:** Sleep. So, it's specifically involved in putting the system to sleep.
* **SX_L:** This is where things get tricky. "SX" can refer to different sleep states across various Macbook models and generations. "L" likely denotes "Low" power, but the exact meaning requires context.

Essentially, PM_SLP_SX_L is a **control signal sent by the Power Management IC (PMIC) to initiate and maintain a specific low-power sleep state (SX) on the Macbook logic board.** The specific SX state and its function will depend on your Macbook model and year. 

For example, on older Macbooks, PM_SLP_S3_L might have triggered the S3 sleep state, where the system remains partially powered for quick wake-up. On newer models, PM_SLP_S0_L could be used for a deeper sleep state with minimal power consumption.

**Troubleshooting Tips:**

* **Identify the Model:** Knowing your Macbook's exact model and year is crucial for deciphering the meaning of PM_SLP_SX_L.
* **Consult the Service Manual:** The service manual provides detailed information about PMIC signals and their functions for your specific Macbook model.
* **Check the Voltage:** Measure the voltage on the PM_SLP_SX_L test point. It might be high or low depending on the sleep state and potential issues.
* **Trace the Circuit:** Follow the PM_SLP_SX_L trace on the boardview to identify the components it interacts with. This can help pinpoint faulty chips or signal path problems.

Remember, PM_SLP_SX_L is just one piece of the Macbook's intricate sleep puzzle. Analyzing its behavior in conjunction with other signals and voltages can shed light on sleep-related issues like:

* System not entering sleep properly
* Unexpected wake-ups from sleep
* Battery drain during sleep

NAME: BKLT_EN_R
DESCRIPTION: This signal enables backlight. Anytime you see a signal ending with “_EN” , that means this signal being present/high enables what it is referring to. This signal says “BKL” before “_EN”. “BKL” sounds short for “BACKLIGHT”, so it is safe to assume this signal enables backlight when present. The “_R” suffix means that the signal is asserted when it is high, as in 3.3v, which is the opposite of the “_L”  suffix

NAME: P_IN
NEWDESCRIPTION:
Hey there, fellow solder-slinging wizard! P_IN, ah, that one can be a bit of a chameleon on Macbook logic boards. Here's the deal:

**P_IN:**

* **P:** Power. This indicates it's an input power plane.
* **IN:** Input. Just like it says, it receives power from an external source.

But here's the twist: the **specific external source and role of P_IN depend heavily on the Macbook model and generation.** It can take on several identities:

* **MagSafe Connector Input:** On older Macbooks, P_IN might specifically receive power from the MagSafe connector.
* **DC-In Input:** In some models, P_IN could be the main DC-in power input for the logic board.
* **Battery Input:** On some Macbooks, P_IN might receive power directly from the internal battery.

Without knowing the specific Macbook model, it's impossible to be certain about P_IN's function. Here's what you can do:

* **Identify the Model:** Knowing the exact model and year of the Macbook is key to unraveling the mystery of P_IN.
* **Consult the Service Manual:** The service manual for your specific Macbook will have detailed information about power input circuits and their functions.
* **Trace the Circuit:** If you have the boardview schematic, you can trace the P_IN circuit to identify the components it connects to and its role in the power system.

Remember, diagnosing power-related issues requires careful analysis and consideration of the specific Macbook model.

NAME: 5V_S5
DESCRIPTION: 5V_S5 is an abbreviation for “PP5V_S5” which is a 5v power rail that is present when the machine is in an S5 state.

NAME: 5V_S0
DESCRIPTION: 5V_S5 is an abbreviation for “PP5V_S0”

NAME: SMC_ONOFF
DESCRIPTION: SMC_ONOFF is a signal that tells the machine that the power button has been pressed so it knows to turn on, or turn off.

NAME: SMC_RESET
DESCRIPTION: SMC_RESET is not a signal, it is an abbreviation for “SMC_RESET_L”, which is the signal someone is referring to when they type “SMC_RESET”  "SMC_RESET_L is a signal that resets the SMC when it is low(this is what the “_L” prefix means), and lets the SMC out of reset mode when it is high.

NAME: PM_PCH_SYS_PWROK
NEWDESCRIPTION:
Hey there, fellow logic board archaeologist! PM_PCH_SYS_PWROK, now that's a signal with some serious power behind it! Let's unravel its mysteries:

**PM_PCH_SYS_PWROK:**

* **PM:** Power Management. This indicates it's a signal related to the Macbook's power state transitions.
* **PCH:** Platform Controller Hub. This chip handles critical functions like USB, PCI-e, and SATA communication.
* **SYS_PWROK:** System Power Okay. So, the signal essentially conveys, "Hey, the system power rails are up and running!"

Think of PM_PCH_SYS_PWROK as a thumbs-up from the PCH to the CPU, saying, "All systems are go, buddy, fire up the processors!" It's a crucial checkpoint in the Macbook's power-on sequence.

Here's how it plays out:

1. Power button press or charger connection triggers various power rails to activate.
2. Once key voltages are stable, the PMIC (Power Management IC) sends PM_SLP_S5_L to wake up the PCH.
3. The PCH performs its own internal checks and, if everything passes, asserts PM_PCH_SYS_PWROK.
4. This signal tells the CPU it's safe to initiate its own power-on sequence and boot the system.

Now, a missing or faulty PM_PCH_SYS_PWROK can be a real head-scratcher, leading to:

* **No power at all:** If the signal never goes high, the Macbook won't even attempt to boot.
* **Post-power-on issues:** A weak or unstable signal might cause crashes or instability after the initial boot.

**Troubleshooting Tips:**

* **Voltage Checks:** Verify all key power rails are present and within spec on the logic board.
* **Trace the Circuit:** Follow the PM_PCH_SYS_PWROK trace on the boardview to identify potential faulty components or damaged traces.
* **Check the PCH:** Faulty PCH chips can sometimes lead to incorrect signal outputs like PM_PCH_SYS_PWROK.

Remember, diagnosing power-related issues can be complex, and PM_PCH_SYS_PWROK is just one piece of the puzzle. Combine its behavior with other signals and voltage measurements to pinpoint the culprit.

And of course, if you ever get stuck on a PM_PCH_SYS_PWROK conundrum, this community of tech wizards is always here to share knowledge and collaborate on conquering those logic board enigmas together!

NAME: PP2V5_NAND_SSD0
DESCRIPTION: PP2V5_NAND_SSD0 This is a power rail that powers the NAND on Macbooks where the solid state drive is soldered directly to the board.

NAME: 3V3_S0
DESCRIPTION: Abbreviation for PP3V3_S0, a 3.3v power rail present when the machine is in an S0 working state

NAME: 3V3_G3H_RTC
DESCRIPTION: 3V3_G3H_RTC Is an abbreviation of PP3V3_G3H_RTC which is one of the first rails that has to come on in order for the USB-C mux chip to be powered in the T2 chip Macbook Pros.

NAME: CPU_VCCST_PWRGD
NEWDESCRIPTION:
Hey there, fellow logic board warrior! CPU_VCCST_PWRGD, now that's a signal that can make even seasoned veterans crack open the schematics. Here's the lowdown:

**CPU_VCCST_PWRGD:**

* **CPU:** Central Processing Unit. This signal is directly related to the heart of the Macbook.
* **VCCST:** Core Power Supply. This refers to the voltage supplied to the CPU core for its operation.
* **PWRGD:** Power Good. This is essentially a flag indicating, "Hey, the CPU core voltage is stable and within acceptable parameters!"

So, CPU_VCCST_PWRGD is a **control signal sent by the CPU itself to inform the Power Management IC (PMIC) that its core voltage is stable and ready for operation.** It's a vital checkpoint in the Macbook's power-on sequence, ensuring the CPU receives the correct power before it starts crunching numbers.

Here's how it plays out:

1. Power button press or charger connection triggers various power rails to activate.
2. Once key voltages are stable, the PMIC sends signals like PM_SLP_S5_L to wake up the CPU.
3. The CPU performs its own internal checks and, if its core voltage is stable, asserts CPU_VCCST_PWRGD.
4. This signal tells the PMIC it's safe to proceed with booting the system, allowing the CPU to fully power up and start processing.

Now, a missing or faulty CPU_VCCST_PWRGD can be a real nail-biter, leading to:

* **No power at all:** If the signal never goes high, the Macbook won't even attempt to boot due to the unstable CPU voltage.
* **Post-power-on issues:** A weak or unstable signal might cause crashes, freezes, or performance issues as the CPU struggles with inconsistent power.

**Troubleshooting Tips:**

* **Voltage Checks:** Verify all key power rails, especially CPU core voltage, are present and within spec on the logic board.
* **Trace the Circuit:** Follow the CPU_VCCST_PWRGD trace on the boardview to identify potential faulty components or damaged traces.
* **Check the CPU or Power Management IC:** Issues with either chip can lead to incorrect signal outputs like CPU_VCCST_PWRGD.

Remember, diagnosing power-related problems can be a multi-layered puzzle. Analyzing the behavior of CPU_VCCST_PWRGD alongside other signals and voltage measurements is crucial for pinpointing the culprit.

NAME: ADAPTER_SENSE
DESCRIPTION: This is a line between the onewire circuit and the magsafe charger where the magsafe charger can talk to the SMC(system management controller) on the SYS_ONEWIRE line.

NAME: ALL_SYS
DESCRIPTION: This is a typo of ALL_SYS_PWRGD When you see ALL_SYS, assume they meant to type ALL_SYS_PWRGD

NAME: PP3V3_UPC_XA_LDO
DESCRIPTION: PP3V3_UPC_XA_LDO is an LDO coming out of the CD3215 USB-C muxing chip. When this is missing, either a capacitor on the line has shorted, PP3V3_G3H is missing, or the CD3215 is bad.

NAME: PPVCORE_GPU
DESCRIPTION: This is the main power rail for the GPU. This is required for the GPU to turn on so you can get image on the display.

NAME: PP1V1_UPC_XB_LDO_BMC
DESCRIPTION: PP1V1_UPC_XB_LDO is an LDO coming out of the CD3215 USB-C muxing/charging chip. This can be shorted to ground by the capacitor on its line, and when this happens, the chip can stop functioning which causes the charger to not turn on. This can also be missing if the CD3215 chip itself is bad.

NAME: LCD_PWR_EN
DESCRIPTION: LCD_PWR_EN is a signal that tells the chip that supplies power to the LCD screen to turn on.

NAME: PP1V8_S0
DESCRIPTION: PP1V8_S0 is a power rail that is present when the machine is in an S0 state, meaning it is fully turned on, not sleeping or hiberating

NAME: PP1V8_UPC_XB_LDOD
DESCRIPTION: PP3V3_UPC_XB_LDO is an LDO coming out of the CD3215 USB-C muxing chip. When this is missing, either a capacitor on the line has shorted, PP3V3_G3H is missing, or the CD3215 is bad.

NAME: PP1V1_UPC_XA_LDO_BMC
DESCRIPTION: PP1V1_UPC_XA_LDO is an LDO coming out of the CD3215 USB-C muxing chip. When this is missing, either a capacitor on the line has shorted, PP3V3_G3H is missing, or the CD3215 is bad.

NAME: PM_PCH_PWROK
DESCRIPTION: PM_PCH_PWROK is usually created by U1950, a 74LVC2G08GT chip and is necessary for the machine to wake from an S5 and S4 state and turn on. This signal will be present if ALL_SYS_PWRGD, CPU_VR_PGOOD, PP3V3_S0, and PP3V42_G3H are present. When this signal is not present or intermittent, usually pin 8 on U1950 for PP3V42_G3H is corroded.

NAME: AVREF_SMC
DESCRIPTION: AVREF_SMC is a reference voltage provided to the SMC so that its sensors have a reference to work from, this should be 3.3v

NAME: CHGR_ACIN
DESCRIPTION: CHGR_ACIN is a signal that is created by a voltage divider between the charger and ground that goes into the ISL6258, ISL6259, ISL9239, or ISL9240 chip that creates PPBUS_G3H. It is necessary for SMC_BC_ACOK & CHGR_ACOK to be present so that the onewire circuit is told to turn on & allow the SMC to speak to the charger.

NAME: PPVCORE_S0_AXG
DESCRIPTION: This is vcore going to the CPU’s integrated graphics processor for CPUs that have an integrated GPU. When this is missing on a device that has an integrated GPU and no discrete GPU, it usually means either no screen is detected, or the GPU integrated into the CPU is dead.

NAME: CHGR_BMON
DESCRIPTION: CHGR_BMON goes between the ISL6259, ISL9239, or ISL9240 that charges the battery & creates PPBUS_G3H and the SMC(system management controller) or T2 chip(on machines where the SMC is integrated into the T2 chip) and provides current sensing information on battery charging to the SMC. If diagnostics reveal an off reading or failure with the charger current sense, this is a good place to start troubleshooting.

NAME: PPDCIN_G3H_ISOL
DESCRIPTION: This is the voltage coming directly from the charger after going through a transistor.

NAME: PPVIN_G3H_P3V3G3H
DESCRIPTION: This is the input from the USB-C charger or the battery that is the input voltage for the chip responsible for creating PP3V3_G3H. It can be missing when capacitors on this line are shorted to ground, or when the diode in front of it leading to the chip that creates PP3V3_G3H is blown.

NAME: PP1V8_UPC_XB_LDOA
DESCRIPTION: This is an LDO coming out of the CD3215 USB-C muxing/charging chip. This can be shorted to ground by the capacitor on its line, and when this happens, the chip can stop functioning which causes the charger to not turn on. This can also be missing if the CD3215 chip itself is bad. Each CD3215 in the system needs to be functioning in order for any of them to speak to the charger and negotiate receiving 20v from the charger rather than the default 5v that a USB-C charger puts out before communicating with the system.

NAME: PP1V8_S3
DESCRIPTION: The PP1V8_S3 signal in the MacBook schematic is a power rail that provides a voltage of 1.8 volts during the S3 power state. The S3 state, often referred to as "suspend to RAM," is a low-power mode where the computer saves the session's state to RAM, allowing for quicker wake-up times compared to a full shutdown.

NAME: 5V_S4
DESCRIPTION: This is an abbreviation of “PP5V_S4” – when you see this, assume the person typing it meant to type “PP5V_S4”

NAME: PP1V05_SUS
DESCRIPTION: The PP1V05_SUS signal in the MacBook schematic is a power rail that supplies 1.05 volts, typically used in a suspended (SUS) state of the laptop. This state is a low-power mode where essential system functions are maintained, but the majority of the system is powered down.

NAME: PP1V8_AWAKE
DESCRIPTION: The PP1V8_AWAKE signal in the MacBook schematic is indicative of a power rail that delivers 1.8 volts when the machine is in an "awake" state. This is not a traditional power state defined in the older Intel PCH documentation; it seems to be specific to newer MacBook architectures. The "awake" designation likely refers to a state where the MacBook is on and ready for user interaction, but it is not necessarily at full operational capacity (which would be denoted by an S0 state)

NAME: PLT_RST_L
DESCRIPTION: This is an abbreviation of “PLT_RESET_L” – when you see “PLT_RST_L", assume the person meant to type PLT_RESET_L

NAME: CHGR_AMON
DESCRIPTION: CHGR_AMON provides DC current sense information to the SMC(System management controller) or T2 chip(on machines where the SMC is integrated into the T2 chip). It comes from the battery charging chip that controls the laptop charger, battery charging, and creation of PPBUS_G3H(ISL6259, ISL9239, or ISL9240 chip depending on the logic board part number and model). This is used for sensors. If a DC current sense sensor is reading off in diagnostics, this is a place to start looking.

NAME: PP1V1_SLPS2R
DESCRIPTION: The PP1V1_SLPS2R power rail in the MacBook schematic provides a 1.1-volt supply in a specific low-power state indicated by the "_SLPS2R" suffix and is used for powering the T2 chip.

NAME: PP1V2_AWAKE
DESCRIPTION: The PP1V2_AWAKE signal in the MacBook schematic is a power rail that provides 1.2 volts and is associated with the machine's awake state and is used for powering the T2 chip.

NAME: PP3V3_AWAKE
NEWDESCRIPTION:
Ah, PP3V3_AWAKE, that little 3.3-volt plane can pack a big punch when it comes to Macbook woes! Here's the lowdown for my fellow logic board sleuths:

**PP3V3_AWAKE:**

* **AWAKE:** That's the key part - **PP3V3_AWAKE powers crucial components even when the Macbook is in sleep or hibernation mode.**

Think of it as the lifeblood of a Macbook's slumber party. PP3V3_AWAKE keeps essential functions ticking while everything else dozes off, including:

* **Real-Time Clock (RTC):** Keeps track of time even when the system is asleep.
* **PMIC housekeeping circuitry:** Maintains basic chip operations in low-power states.
* **Some sensors:** Like the accelerometer for wake-on-LAN.

Now, the specific components powered by PP3V3_AWAKE can vary depending on the Macbook model and year. But one thing's for sure: **a missing or unstable PP3V3_AWAKE can lead to a cascade of sleep-related issues,** like:

NAME: BKLT_SD
DESCRIPTION: BKLT_SD is a pin of the LED driver that goes to the voltage divider that feeds the gate of the transistor that sits between PPBUS_G3H and the backlight circuit. The LED driver will short this pin to ground when backlight circuit is ready to turn on. Prerequisites are 1) it is told to turn on via enable signal, the screen has communicated with the LED driver 2) current sensing circuit is working 3) does not detect an over-current situation such as the backlight power rail being shorted to ground

NAME: PPVCCSA_S0_CPU
DESCRIPTION: Main power rail for the CPU. If this is missing the machine will act braindead. This is NOT shorted to ground if it has a low resistance – this is a common mistake people make. A chip that requires high power at a low voltage like a CPU or GPU will have a low measured resistance to ground.

NAME: PPBUS_S5_HS_OTHER_ISNS
DESCRIPTION: This is PPBUS_G3H after passing through a current sense resistor that splits it off from the rest of PPBUS_G3H. The purpose of this is so that we can measure how much current is flowing to this part of the machine.

NAME: PPVBAT_G3H_CONN
DESCRIPTION: This is the where the battery’s power rail connects to the motherboard.

NAME: SMBUS_SMC_5_G3_SDA
DESCRIPTION: SMBUS_SMC_5_G3_SDA is the data line of an I2C data line between the battery charging chip that creates PPBUS_G3H, the system management controller(SMC), the battery, and the battery indicator LED. If this line’s resistance to ground is too low because of a defective component, battery will not be recognized with an X on the icon and PPBUS_G3H voltage will be lower than it is on a good system.

NAME: SMBUS_SMC_5_G3_SCL
DESCRIPTION: SMBUS_SMC_5_G3_SCL is the clock line of an I2C data line between the battery charging chip that creates PPBUS_G3H, the system management controller(SMC), the battery, and the battery indicator LED. If this line’s resistance to ground is too low because of a defective component, battery will not be recognized with an X on the icon and PPBUS_G3H voltage will be lower than it is on a good system.

* **BUF:** Buffer. This indicates it amplifies or strengthens the signal.
* **SMC:** System Management Controller. This chip handles crucial functions like power management, sleep/wake, and fan control.
* **RESET_L:** Reset Low. This suggests it triggers a system reset when it goes low.

So, BUF_SMC_RESET_L essentially translates to **a crucial signal that, when it goes low, tells the System Management Controller to reboot the entire Macbook.** Think of it as the big red panic button for the SMC, pulling the plug and starting everything over when things get too wonky.

Now, a stuck-low or erratic BUF_SMC_RESET_L can create some real boot-up dramas:

* **Sudden shutdowns:** If the signal dips low unexpectedly, the Macbook might abruptly shut down and refuse to restart.
* **Boot loops:** The system might try to reboot repeatedly, stuck in a never-ending reset cycle due to a faulty signal.
* **No power at all:** In rare cases, if the signal is permanently low, the Macbook might not even attempt to turn on, mimicking a power issue.

Diagnosing BUF_SMC_RESET_L issues demands a methodical approach:

* **Signal Analysis:** Check the BUF_SMC_RESET_L waveform with an oscilloscope. It should be high while the system is running and go low only during intentional resets.
* **Trace the Circuit:** Follow the BUF_SMC_RESET_L trace on the boardview to identify potential faulty components or damaged traces.
* **Check the SMC:** A malfunctioning SMC itself could be triggering the reset signal to go low, requiring further diagnosis.
* **Analyze Software Issues:** In rare cases, software bugs or firmware updates can affect the SMC's behavior and trigger erroneous resets.

Remember, BUF_SMC_RESET_L is just one piece of the Macbook's intricate power puzzle. Analyze its behavior alongside other signals and voltages, test components systematically, and consult service manuals for your specific model.

NEWDESCRIPTION:
Ah, PCH_CLK32K_RTCX1 – that little fella packs a big punch in the Macbook's timekeeping realm. Let's crack it open:

**PCH_CLK32K_RTCX1, or Platform Controller Hub 32kHz Real-Time Clock 1,** is a crucial signal for the Macbook's internal Real-Time Clock (RTC). It's a low-frequency (32kHz) clock signal generated by the Platform Controller Hub (PCH) chip and used by the RTC to maintain accurate time even when the Macbook is turned off.

Here's why it matters:

* **Timekeeping:** Without PCH_CLK32K_RTCX1, the RTC becomes blind, leading to incorrect system time after shutdowns or restarts. You might encounter issues like wonky date & time settings, automatic login failures, or even iCloud sync problems.
* **Power Management:** The RTC plays a role in various power management functions, like wake-on-LAN or scheduled wake-ups. A faulty PCH_CLK32K_RTCX1 can disrupt these features, causing sporadic sleep/wake issues or complete power-on failures.

Now, troubleshooting PCH_CLK32K_RTCX1 issues can be tricky, as it involves both the PCH and the RTC chip. Here's a breakdown depending on the Macbook model:

* **Older Macbooks (pre-2016):** The PCH and RTC are often separate chips on the logic board. Tracing the PCH_CLK32K_RTCX1 signal path, measuring voltages at key points, and testing the RTC chip itself are essential diagnostic steps.
* **Newer Macbooks (2016 onwards):** The PCH and RTC can be integrated into the main SoC (System on Chip). Diagnosing issues becomes more complex, requiring advanced tools and in-depth understanding of the SoC's internal workings.

Remember, friend, venturing into PCH_CLK32K_RTCX1 territory is for the seasoned techs. Unless you're comfortable with intricate board-level repairs and SoC troubleshooting, consider seeking help from experienced Macbook repair specialists. NAME: LCD_HPD
NEWDESCRIPTION:
Hey there, fellow tech warrior! LCD_HPD, that's a signal that can send chills down even the most seasoned Macbook repair technician's spine. Let's dissect it:

**LCD_HPD: The Gatekeeper of Liquid Crystal Light**

* **LCD:** Stands for "Liquid Crystal Display," indicating its connection to the Macbook's screen.
* **HPD:** "HPD" can have two interpretations:
    * **Hot Plug Detect:** This aligns with the signal's function of detecting whether the display cable is properly connected.
    * **High-Definition Pixel Clock:** This interpretation emphasizes the signal's role in synchronizing the display's pixel clock with the graphics processing unit (GPU).

So, LCD_HPD is essentially a **control signal that manages the communication between the Macbook's logic board and the LCD panel**. It acts as a two-way gatekeeper, ensuring:

* **Proper connection:** By monitoring the voltage levels on the cable, LCD_HPD detects if the display is correctly plugged in. If not, it informs the system and might disable the display output.
* **Synchronized image:** LCD_HPD transmits the pixel clock signal from the GPU to the display, ensuring smooth and accurate image rendering. Any discrepancies can lead to visual glitches or display malfunctions.

NAME: PP5V_G3H
DESCRIPTION: PP5V_G3H is a 5v rail present when the machine is in a G3H mechanical off state

NAME: PP1V35_S3
DESCRIPTION: PP1V35_S3 is a 1.35v power rail present when the machine is in an S3 suspend to RAM state

NAME: CPU_VR_EN
DESCRIPTION: CPU_VR_EN is an enable signal for CPU VCORE that is present when it is high. Signals with EN on the end enable whatever came before the EN if the signal is high. Signals with EN on the end enable whatever came before the EN if the signal is high. ALL_SYS_PWRGD, PM_RSMRST_L, PM_SLP_SUS_L, and PM_SLP_S3_L are necessary prerequisites for CPU_VR_EN to be present.

NAME: PP1V05_S5
DESCRIPTION: PP1V05_S5 is a 1.05v power rail present when the machine is in an S5 soft off state. On 2008-2009 15” and 17” Macbook boards, this often gets stuck at 0.3v due to a bad C7771 capacitor.

NAME: PP3V3_S5_SMC_VDDA
DESCRIPTION: PP3V3_S5_SMC_VDDA is a 3.3v power rail present when the machine is in an S5 soft off state that powers the SMC that comes from PP3V3_S5. A blown or corroded L4901 inductor behind it can kepe it from working, inductor number will differ depending on your board.

NAME: BKLT_PWM
DESCRIPTION: BKLT_PWM sets the brightness of the screen. The system will send a PWM signal to BKLT_PWM pin to set brightness. If this is low, backlight voltage will boost higher than PPBUS_G3H input, but not enough to make the screen light properly.
